## Phase 3: Spike Detection (No Lambda)

Instead of AWS Lambda, use **APScheduler** running inside the FastAPI process:

```python
# app/services/spike_detector.py
from apscheduler.schedulers.asyncio import AsyncIOScheduler

SPIKE_SQL = """
WITH daily AS (
    SELECT DATE(billing_period_start) as day, provider,
           SUM(billed_cost) as cost
    FROM focus_billing
    WHERE billing_period_start >= NOW() - INTERVAL '14 days'
    GROUP BY 1, 2
),
baselines AS (
    SELECT provider, AVG(cost) as avg_daily
    FROM daily WHERE day < CURRENT_DATE - 1
    GROUP BY provider
)
SELECT d.day, d.provider, d.cost, b.avg_daily,
       ((d.cost - b.avg_daily) / NULLIF(b.avg_daily, 0) * 100) as pct_change
FROM daily d JOIN baselines b ON d.provider = b.provider
WHERE d.day >= CURRENT_DATE - 1
  AND d.cost > b.avg_daily * 1.20
ORDER BY pct_change DESC
"""

async def check_for_spikes():
    """Runs every hour via APScheduler."""
    spikes = await db.fetch_all(SPIKE_SQL)
    if spikes:
        # Trigger agent chain automatically
        await trigger_analysis(spikes)
        await send_alert(spikes)  # Slack/Email/webhook
```

```python
# In main.py lifespan
scheduler = AsyncIOScheduler()
scheduler.add_job(check_for_spikes, "interval", hours=1)
scheduler.start()
```

> [!TIP]
> **Why APScheduler over Lambda?**
> - Runs in-process — no AWS dependency
> - Works on any cloud, Docker, or local machine
> - Can be swapped for Celery Beat, K8s CronJob, or cloud-specific scheduler later

